{"title_page": "Dido building Carthage", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=May 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2016}}\n{{italic title}}\n[[File:Turner Dido Building Carthage.jpg|thumb|300px|J. M. W. Turner, ''Dido building Carthage, or The Rise of the Carthaginian Empire'', 1815]]\n\n'''''Dido building Carthage, or The Rise of the Carthaginian Empire''''' is an oil on canvas painting by [[J. M. W. Turner]].  The painting is one of Turner's most important works, greatly influenced by the luminous classical landscapes of [[Claude Lorrain]].  Turner described it as his [[chef d'oeuvre]].  First exhibited at the [[Royal Academy summer exhibition]] in 1815, Turner kept the painting until he left it to the nation in the [[Turner Bequest]].  It has been held by the [[National Gallery]] in London since 1856.  \n\nThe subject is a classical landscape taken from [[Virgil]]'s ''[[Aeneid]]''.  The figure in blue and white on the left is [[Dido (Queen of Carthage)|Dido]], directing the builders of the new city of [[Carthage]].  The figure in front of her, wearing armour and facing away from the viewer, may be her [[Troy|Trojan]] lover [[Aeneas]].  Some children are playing with a flimsy toy boat in the water, symbolising the growing but fragile naval power of Carthage, while the tomb of her dead husband [[Sychaeus]], on the right side of the painting, on the other bank of the estuary, foreshadows the eventual doom of Carthage.  \n\nThe painting measures {{convert|155.5|cm}} by {{convert| 230|cm}} with the top half of the painting dominated by an intense yellow sunrise, symbolising the dawn of a new empire.  The [[1815 eruption of Mount Tambora|eruption of Mount Tambora]] in April 1815 created magnificent sunrises and sunsets which may have inspired Turner's paintings in this period.  The painting was widely admired when it was first exhibited at the [[Royal Academy summer exhibition]] in 1815 together ''Crossing the Brook'', a pastoral landscape of the [[River Tamar]] in Devon also inspired by Claude.  However, Turner's work was criticised by Sir [[George Beaumont]], who complained that it was \"painted in false taste, not true to nature\" and did not reach the heights of Claude's works.  Turner exhibited a companion piece, ''[[The Decline of the Carthaginian Empire]]'', at the summer exhibition in 1817.\n\nIn the first draft of his first will in 1829, Turner stipulated that he should be buried in the canvas of ''Dido building Carthage'', but changed his mind to make a donation of the painting and ''The Decline of the Carthaginian Empire'' to the National Gallery, on condition that his two paintings should always be hung either side of Claude's ''[[Seaport with the Embarkation of the Queen of Sheba]]'', a painting that Turner first saw when it was part of the [[Angerstein collection]] which later became the nucleus for the National Gallery.  His revised will of 1831 changed the bequest, so ''Dido building Carthage'' would be accompanied by ''[[Sun rising through Vapour]]'', and the two works would be exhibited alongside ''Seaport with the Embarkation of the Queen of Sheba'' and ''[[Landscape with the Marriage of Isaac and Rebecca]]'' (also known as ''The Mill'').  A codicil in 1848 donated the remainder of his completed works to the new National Gallery in Trafalgar Square, so they could be displayed together.  The [[Turner Bequest]] was contested by his relatives, but resolved by 1856 when the works were acquired by the National Gallery.  Most of Turner's works eventually moved to the [[Tate Gallery]] in the early 20th century, but ''Dido building Carthage'' and ''Sun rising through Vapour'' remain at the National Gallery, shown with the Claudes; a few other selected works by Turner, including ''[[Rain, Steam and Speed \u2013 The Great Western Railway|Rain, Steam and Speed]]'' and ''[[The Fighting Temeraire]]'' remain as examples of English painting at the National Gallery.\n\n<gallery widths=\"200px\" heights=\"200px\">\nFile:Claude Lorrain 008.jpg|Claude's ''[[The Embarkation of the Queen of Sheba]]'', 1648\nFile:Claude Lorrain, The Mill.jpg|Claude's ''Landscape with the Marriage of Isaac and Rebecca'', 1648\nFile:Joseph Mallord William Turner - The Decline of the Carthaginian Empire - WGA23169.jpg|Turner's ''The Decline of the Carthaginian Empire'', 1817\nFile:Joseph Mallord William Turner 049.jpg|Turner's ''Sun Rising through Vapour, Fishermen Cleaning and Selling Fish'', 1807\nFile:William Turner - Crossing the Brook.jpg|Turner's ''Crossing the Brook'', 1815\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n* [http://www.nationalgallery.org.uk/paintings/joseph-mallord-william-turner-dido-building-carthage National Gallery]\n* [https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2012/mar/08/jmw-turner-english-claude JMW Turner, the English Claude], ''The Guardian'', 8 March 2012\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=s-qOzuMCwkkC&pg=PA42 ''J. M. W. Turner: The Making of a Modern Artist''], Sam Smiles, pp. 42\u201344, 126\u2013128\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=1pehApifVPcC&pg=PA183 ''Academies, Museums, and Canons of Art''], Gillian Perry, Colin Cunningham, pp. 183\u2013185\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=uxroHjm2QAIC&pg=PA63 ''Angel in the Sun: Turner's Vision of History''], Gerald E. Finley, pp. 63\u201367\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=reMQtMT0cRsC&pg=PA129 ''Cultivating Picturacy: Visual Art And Verbal Interventions''], James A. W. Heffernan, pp. 129\u2013131\n* [http://www.turnersociety.org.uk/Turner_biography.pdf Turner biography], Turner Society\n\n{{J. M. W. Turner}}\n{{Dido and Aeneas}}\n{{Aeneid}}\n\n[[Category:1815 paintings]]\n[[Category:Collections of the National Gallery, London]]\n[[Category:Paintings by J. M. W. Turner]]\n[[Category:Water in art]]\n[[Category:Sun in art]]\n[[Category:Works based on the Aeneid]]\n[[Category:Paintings based on literature]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=May 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2016}}\n{{italic title}}\n[[File:Turner Dido Building Carthage.jpg|thumb|300px|J. M. W. Turner, ''Dido building Carthage, or The Rise of the Carthaginian Empire'', 1815]]\n\n'''''Dido building Carthage, or The Rise of the Carthaginian Empire''''' is an oil on canvas painting by [[J. M. W. Turner]].  The painting is one of Turner's most important works, greatly influenced by the luminous classical landscapes of [[Claude Lorraine]].  Turner described it as his [[chef d'oeuvre]].  First exhibited at the [[Royal Academy summer exhibition]] in 1815, Turner kept the painting until he left it to the nation in the [[Turner Bequest]].  It has been held by the [[National Gallery]] in London since 1856.  \n\nThe subject is a classical landscape taken from [[Virgil]]'s ''[[Aeneid]]''.  The figure in blue and white on the left is [[Dido (Queen of Carthage)|Dido]], directing the builders of the new city of [[Carthage]].  The figure in front of her, wearing armour and facing away from the viewer, may be her [[Troy|Trojan]] lover [[Aeneas]].  Some children are playing with a flimsy toy boat in the water, symbolising the growing but fragile naval power of Carthage, while the tomb of her dead husband [[Sychaeus]], on the right side of the painting, on the other bank of the estuary, foreshadows the eventual doom of Carthage.  \n\nThe painting measures {{convert|155.5|cm}} by {{convert| 230|cm}} with the top half of the painting dominated by an intense yellow sunrise, symbolising the dawn of a new empire.  The [[1815 eruption of Mount Tambora|eruption of Mount Tambora]] in April 1815 created magnificent sunrises and sunsets which may have inspired Turner's paintings in this period.  The painting was widely admired when it was first exhibited at the [[Royal Academy summer exhibition]] in 1815 together ''Crossing the Brook'', a pastoral landscape of the [[River Tamar]] in Devon also inspired by Claude.  However, Turner's work was criticised by Sir [[George Beaumont]], who complained that it was \"painted in false taste, not true to nature\" and did not reach the heights of Claude's works.  Turner exhibited a companion piece, ''[[The Decline of the Carthaginian Empire]]'', at the summer exhibition in 1817.\n\nIn the first draft of his first will in 1829, Turner stipulated that he should be buried in the canvas of ''Dido building Carthage'', but changed his mind to make a donation of the painting and ''The Decline of the Carthaginian Empire'' to the National Gallery, on condition that his two paintings should always be hung either side of Claude's ''[[Seaport with the Embarkation of the Queen of Sheba]]'', a painting that Turner first saw when it was part of the [[Angerstein collection]] which later became the nucleus for the National Gallery.  His revised will of 1831 changed the bequest, so ''Dido building Carthage'' would be accompanied by ''[[Sun rising through Vapour]]'', and the two works would be exhibited alongside ''Seaport with the Embarkation of the Queen of Sheba'' and ''[[Landscape with the Marriage of Isaac and Rebecca]]'' (also known as ''The Mill'').  A codicil in 1848 donated the remainder of his completed works to the new National Gallery in Trafalgar Square, so they could be displayed together.  The [[Turner Bequest]] was contested by his relatives, but resolved by 1856 when the works were acquired by the National Gallery.  Most of Turner's works eventually moved to the [[Tate Gallery]] in the early 20th century, but ''Dido building Carthage'' and ''Sun rising through Vapour'' remain at the National Gallery, shown with the Claudes; a few other selected works by Turner, including ''[[Rain, Steam and Speed \u2013 The Great Western Railway|Rain, Steam and Speed]]'' and ''[[The Fighting Temeraire]]'' remain as examples of English painting at the National Gallery.\n\n<gallery widths=\"200px\" heights=\"200px\">\nFile:Claude Lorrain 008.jpg|Claude's ''[[The Embarkation of the Queen of Sheba]]'', 1648\nFile:Claude Lorrain, The Mill.jpg|Claude's ''Landscape with the Marriage of Isaac and Rebecca'', 1648\nFile:Joseph Mallord William Turner - The Decline of the Carthaginian Empire - WGA23169.jpg|Turner's ''The Decline of the Carthaginian Empire'', 1817\nFile:Joseph Mallord William Turner 049.jpg|Turner's ''Sun Rising through Vapour, Fishermen Cleaning and Selling Fish'', 1807\nFile:William Turner - Crossing the Brook.jpg|Turner's ''Crossing the Brook'', 1815\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n* [http://www.nationalgallery.org.uk/paintings/joseph-mallord-william-turner-dido-building-carthage National Gallery]\n* [https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2012/mar/08/jmw-turner-english-claude JMW Turner, the English Claude], ''The Guardian'', 8 March 2012\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=s-qOzuMCwkkC&pg=PA42 ''J. M. W. Turner: The Making of a Modern Artist''], Sam Smiles, pp. 42\u201344, 126\u2013128\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=1pehApifVPcC&pg=PA183 ''Academies, Museums, and Canons of Art''], Gillian Perry, Colin Cunningham, pp. 183\u2013185\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=uxroHjm2QAIC&pg=PA63 ''Angel in the Sun: Turner's Vision of History''], Gerald E. Finley, pp. 63\u201367\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=reMQtMT0cRsC&pg=PA129 ''Cultivating Picturacy: Visual Art And Verbal Interventions''], James A. W. Heffernan, pp. 129\u2013131\n* [http://www.turnersociety.org.uk/Turner_biography.pdf Turner biography], Turner Society\n\n{{J. M. W. Turner}}\n{{Dido and Aeneas}}\n{{Aeneid}}\n\n[[Category:1815 paintings]]\n[[Category:Collections of the National Gallery, London]]\n[[Category:Paintings by J. M. W. Turner]]\n[[Category:Water in art]]\n[[Category:Sun in art]]\n[[Category:Works based on the Aeneid]]\n[[Category:Paintings based on literature]]\n", "name_user": "Phalaina7", "label": "safe", "comment": "name was misspelled. (\"Claude Lorraine\" -> \"Claude Lorrain\")", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dido_building_Carthage"}
{"title_page": "Belgian Canadians", "text_new": "{{Infobox ethnic group\n|group      = Belgian Canadians\n|image      = \n|population = '''176,615'''<br />(by ancestry, <small>[[Canada 2011 Census|2011 Census]]</small>)<ref name=\"Belgian Canadians\">{{cite web |url=http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/nhs-enm/2011/dp-pd/dt-td/Rp-eng.cfm?TABID=2&LANG=E&APATH=3&DETAIL=0&DIM=0&FL=A&FREE=0&GC=0&GID=1118296&GK=0&GRP=0&PID=105396&PRID=0&PTYPE=105277&S=0&SHOWALL=0&SUB=0&Temporal=2013&THEME=95&VID=0&VNAMEE=&VNAMEF=&D1=0&D2=0&D3=0&D4=0&D5=0&D6=0 |author=[[Statistics Canada]] |title=2011 National Household Survey: Data tables |accessdate=11 February 2014}}</ref>\n|popplace   = [[Montreal]], [[Toronto]], [[Calgary]], [[Vancouver]], [[Edmonton]], [[Winnipeg]], [[Ottawa]]\n|region1    = \n|pop1       = \n|region2    = \n|pop2       = \n|region3    = \n|pop3       = \n|region4    = \n|pop4       = \n|languages  = [[English language|English]]{{\u00b7}}[[French language|French]]{{\u00b7}}[[Dutch language|Dutch]]{{\u00b7}}[[German language|German]]\n|religions  = [[Christianity]]\n|related    = [[Dutch Canadian]]s{{\u00b7}}[[French Canadian]]s{{\u00b7}}[[Canadians of German ethnicity|German Canadians]]\n}}\n'''Belgian Canadians''' ([[French language|French]]: ''Canadiens belges'') are [[Canadians|Canadian citizen]]s of Belgian ancestry or [[Belgium]]-born people who reside in Canada. According to the [[Canada 2011 Census|2011 Census]] there were 176,615 Canadians who claimed full or partial Belgian ancestry.<ref name=\"Belgian Canadians\"/>\n\n==subscribe to sidepiece==\nSince the 1890s, many male sidepieces have married female Walloon immigrants, and they have given birth to new children of mixed Walloon-sidepiece descent.\n\n== History ==\nPeople from the [[Southern Netherlands]] (present-day Belgium) first arrived in the 1660s. A trickle of artisans came to New France before the 1750s. In the mid-19th century there were enough arrivals to open part-time consulates in Montreal, Quebec City and Halifax. After 1859 the main attraction was free farm land. After 1867 the national government gave immigrants from Belgium a preferred status, and encouraged emigration to the Francophone Catholic communities of Quebec and Manitoba. \u00c9douard Simaeys became a part-time paid Canadian agent in Belgium to publicize opportunities in Canada and facilitate immigration. The steamship companies prepared their own brochures and offered package deals to farm families.  By 1898 there was a full-time Canadian office in Antwerp which provided pamphlets, lectures and specific travel advice. By 1906 some 2000 Belgians a year were arriving, most with skills in agriculture. A third wave of immigration took place after 1945, with urban areas the destination.  The 1961 census counted 61,000 Canadians of Belgian ancestry.<ref>Paul R. Magocsi, ''Encyclopedia of Canada's peoples'' (1999) pp 257-69</ref>  \n\nBelgian immigration to [[western Canada]] in the late 19th and early 20th century attracted the attention of the Belgian government. It enacted laws and regulations to protect the emigrants and guarantee adequate travel conditions.  Provision was made to assist emigrants who decided to return to Belgium.  Starting in the 1860s consular officials made on-site visits to inspect conditions in Canada, which eagerly welcomed the new arrivals. The Catholic church was likewise welcoming, and a number of priests emigrated. The [[Walloons|Walloon]] immigrants discovered they could continue to speak French in Canada, while the [[Flemish]] quickly learned English.  The Belgians formed no national organizations but they were active in local affairs. Some settled in towns such as [[Saint Boniface, Manitoba]], but most became farmers who specialized in dairy farming, sugar beets and market gardening.  After 1920 there was a move to western Alberta, with an economy based on ranching, horse breeding, and sugar beets.<ref>Cornelius J. Jaenen, ''Promoters, Planters, and Pioneers: The Course and Context of Belgian Settlement in Western Canada'' (University of Calgary Press, 2011)</ref>\n\nDuring the Second World War, Belgian \u00e9migr\u00e9s from Canada and elsewhere in the Americas were formed into the 2nd Fusilier Battalion of the [[Free Belgian Forces]], which was based in Canada.<ref>{{cite book|last=Thomas|first=Nigel|title=Foreign Volunteers of the Allied Forces, 1939\u201345|year=1991|publisher=Osprey|location=London|isbn=978-1-85532-136-6|pages=15\u20136}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Canada|Belgium}}\n* [[European Canadians]]\n* [[Belgian Americans]]\n* [[Belgium\u2013Canada relations]]\n* [[Flemish Canadians]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Magocsi, Paul R. ''Encyclopedia of Canada's peoples'' (1999) pp 257\u201369\n* Jaenen, Cornelius J. ''Promoters, Planters, and Pioneers: The Course and Context of Belgian Settlement in Western Canada'' (University of Calgary Press, 2011)\n* Magee, Joan. ''The Belgians in Ontario: A History'' (Dundurn Press, 1987)\n\n{{People of Canada}}\n{{Belgian diaspora}}\n\n[[Category:Belgian Canadian| ]]\n[[Category:European Canadian|Belgian]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Flemish descent|*]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Belgian descent|*]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Canada|Belgian]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox ethnic group\n|group      = Belgian Canadians\n|image      = \n|population = '''176,615'''<br />(by ancestry, <small>[[Canada 2011 Census|2011 Census]]</small>)<ref name=\"Belgian Canadians\">{{cite web |url=http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/nhs-enm/2011/dp-pd/dt-td/Rp-eng.cfm?TABID=2&LANG=E&APATH=3&DETAIL=0&DIM=0&FL=A&FREE=0&GC=0&GID=1118296&GK=0&GRP=0&PID=105396&PRID=0&PTYPE=105277&S=0&SHOWALL=0&SUB=0&Temporal=2013&THEME=95&VID=0&VNAMEE=&VNAMEF=&D1=0&D2=0&D3=0&D4=0&D5=0&D6=0 |author=[[Statistics Canada]] |title=2011 National Household Survey: Data tables |accessdate=11 February 2014}}</ref>\n|popplace   = [[Montreal]], [[Toronto]], [[Calgary]], [[Vancouver]], [[Edmonton]], [[Winnipeg]], [[Ottawa]]\n|region1    = \n|pop1       = \n|region2    = \n|pop2       = \n|region3    = \n|pop3       = \n|region4    = \n|pop4       = \n|languages  = [[English language|English]]{{\u00b7}}[[French language|French]]{{\u00b7}}[[Dutch language|Dutch]]{{\u00b7}}[[German language|German]]\n|religions  = [[Christianity]]\n|related    = [[Dutch Canadian]]s{{\u00b7}}[[French Canadian]]s{{\u00b7}}[[Canadians of German ethnicity|German Canadians]]\n}}\n'''Belgian Canadians''' ([[French language|French]]: ''Canadiens belges'') are [[Canadians|Canadian citizen]]s of Belgian ancestry or [[Belgium]]-born people who reside in Canada. According to the [[Canada 2011 Census|2011 Census]] there were 176,615 Canadians who claimed full or partial Belgian ancestry.<ref name=\"Belgian Canadians\"/>\n\n==Walloon Quebecers==\nSince the 1890s, many male Quebecers have married female Walloon immigrants, and they have given birth to new children of mixed Walloon-Quebecer descent.\n\n== History ==\nPeople from the [[Southern Netherlands]] (present-day Belgium) first arrived in the 1660s. A trickle of artisans came to New France before the 1750s. In the mid-19th century there were enough arrivals to open part-time consulates in Montreal, Quebec City and Halifax. After 1859 the main attraction was free farm land. After 1867 the national government gave immigrants from Belgium a preferred status, and encouraged emigration to the Francophone Catholic communities of Quebec and Manitoba. \u00c9douard Simaeys became a part-time paid Canadian agent in Belgium to publicize opportunities in Canada and facilitate immigration. The steamship companies prepared their own brochures and offered package deals to farm families.  By 1898 there was a full-time Canadian office in Antwerp which provided pamphlets, lectures and specific travel advice. By 1906 some 2000 Belgians a year were arriving, most with skills in agriculture. A third wave of immigration took place after 1945, with urban areas the destination.  The 1961 census counted 61,000 Canadians of Belgian ancestry.<ref>Paul R. Magocsi, ''Encyclopedia of Canada's peoples'' (1999) pp 257-69</ref>  \n\nBelgian immigration to [[western Canada]] in the late 19th and early 20th century attracted the attention of the Belgian government. It enacted laws and regulations to protect the emigrants and guarantee adequate travel conditions.  Provision was made to assist emigrants who decided to return to Belgium.  Starting in the 1860s consular officials made on-site visits to inspect conditions in Canada, which eagerly welcomed the new arrivals. The Catholic church was likewise welcoming, and a number of priests emigrated. The [[Walloons|Walloon]] immigrants discovered they could continue to speak French in Canada, while the [[Flemish]] quickly learned English.  The Belgians formed no national organizations but they were active in local affairs. Some settled in towns such as [[Saint Boniface, Manitoba]], but most became farmers who specialized in dairy farming, sugar beets and market gardening.  After 1920 there was a move to western Alberta, with an economy based on ranching, horse breeding, and sugar beets.<ref>Cornelius J. Jaenen, ''Promoters, Planters, and Pioneers: The Course and Context of Belgian Settlement in Western Canada'' (University of Calgary Press, 2011)</ref>\n\nDuring the Second World War, Belgian \u00e9migr\u00e9s from Canada and elsewhere in the Americas were formed into the 2nd Fusilier Battalion of the [[Free Belgian Forces]], which was based in Canada.<ref>{{cite book|last=Thomas|first=Nigel|title=Foreign Volunteers of the Allied Forces, 1939\u201345|year=1991|publisher=Osprey|location=London|isbn=978-1-85532-136-6|pages=15\u20136}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Canada|Belgium}}\n* [[European Canadians]]\n* [[Belgian Americans]]\n* [[Belgium\u2013Canada relations]]\n* [[Flemish Canadians]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Magocsi, Paul R. ''Encyclopedia of Canada's peoples'' (1999) pp 257\u201369\n* Jaenen, Cornelius J. ''Promoters, Planters, and Pioneers: The Course and Context of Belgian Settlement in Western Canada'' (University of Calgary Press, 2011)\n* Magee, Joan. ''The Belgians in Ontario: A History'' (Dundurn Press, 1987)\n\n{{People of Canada}}\n{{Belgian diaspora}}\n\n[[Category:Belgian Canadian| ]]\n[[Category:European Canadian|Belgian]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Flemish descent|*]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Belgian descent|*]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Canada|Belgian]]\n", "name_user": "174.3.206.182", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eWalloon Quebecers)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Belgian_Canadians"}
{"title_page": "Albert Manent", "text_new": "'''Albert Manent i Segimon''' (23 September 1930 &ndash; 14 April 2014) was a [[Spain|Spanish]] writer and cultural activist. He was mostly involved in the field of [[Catalan language|Catalan]]. Manent was the son of the writer [[Mari\u00e0 Manent]]. He graduated the subject of law and in Catalan [[philology]]. He was born in [[Premia de Dalt]], Spain.\n\nIn 1995 he won the [[Ramon Llull Novel Award]] for his biography ''Mari\u00e0 Manent, biograf\u00eda \u00edntima i liter\u00e0ria''.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://elpais.com/diario/1995/03/10/cultura/794790005_850215.html |title=Albert Manent gana el Premio Ramon Llull con una biograf\u00eda de su padre |trans-title=Albert Manent Wins the Ramon Llull Award with a Biography of His Father |first=Xavier |last=Moret |work=[[El Pa\u00eds]] |location=Barcelona |language=Spanish |date=10 March 1995 |access-date=21 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nManent died in [[Madrid]] from an illness, aged 83.<ref>[http://www.lavanguardia.com/cultura/20140414/54405820774/muere-albert-manent-premi-honor-lletres-catalanes.html La Vanguardia.com: Muere Albert Manent, Premi d'Honor de les Lletres Catalanes]</ref><ref>[http://ccaa.elpais.com/ccaa/2014/04/15/catalunya/1397517039_649724.html El Pa\u00eds: Muere Albert Manent, clave en la trastienda cultural catalana]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://lletra.uoc.edu/ca/autor/albert-manent Webpage devoted to Albert Manent at LletrA (UOC), Catalan Literature Online] (Catalan)\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Manent, Albert}}\n[[Category:1930 births]]\n[[Category:2014 deaths]]\n[[Category:Spanish male writers]]\n[[Category:Spanish activists]]\n\n\n{{Spain-writer-stub}}\n{{Activist-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Albert Manent i Segimon''' (23 September 1930 &ndash; 14 April 2014) was a [[Spain|Spanish]] writer and cultural activist. He was mostly involved in the field of [[Catalan language|Catalan]]. Manent was the son of the writer [[Mari\u00e0 Manent]]. He graduated the subject of law and in Catalan [[philology]]. He was born in [[Premia de Dalt]], Spain.\n\nIn 1995 he won the [[Ramon Llull Novel Award]] for his biography ''Mari\u00e0 Manent, biograf\u00eda \u00edntima i liter\u00e0ria''.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://elpais.com/diario/1995/03/10/cultura/794790005_850215.html |title=Albert Manent gana el Premio Ramon Llull con una biograf\u00eda de su padre |trans-title=Albert Manent Wins the Ramon Llull Award with a Biography of His Father |first=Xavier |last=Moret |work=[[El Pa\u00eds]] |location=Barcelona |language=Spanish |date=10 March 1995 |access-date=21 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nManent died in [[Madrid]] from an illness, aged 83.<ref>[http://www.lavanguardia.com/cultura/20140414/54405820774/muere-albert-manent-premi-honor-lletres-catalanes.html La Vanguardia.com: Muere Albert Manent, Premi d'Honor de les Lletres Catalanes]</ref><ref>[http://ccaa.elpais.com/ccaa/2014/04/15/catalunya/1397517039_649724.html El Pa\u00eds: Muere Albert Manent, clave en la trastienda cultural catalana]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://lletra.uoc.edu/ca/autor/albert-manent Webpage devoted to Albert Manent at LletrA (UOC), Catalan Literature Online] (Catalan)\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Manent, Albert}}\n[[Category:1930 births]]\n[[Category:2014 deaths]]\n[[Category:Spanish male writers]]\n[[Category:Spanish activists]]\n\n\n{{Spain-writer-stub}}\n{{Activist-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Albert_Manent"}
{"title_page": "Adrian Beecroft", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name           = Adrian Beecroft\n| image          =\n| image_size     =\n| caption        =\n| birth_date     = 20 May 1947\n| birth_place    = [[Yorkshire]], [[England]]\n| death_place    =\n| education      = [[Hymers College]]<br/>[[Queen's College, Oxford]]<br/>[[Harvard Business School]]\n| occupation     = [[Angel investor]]\n| spouse         = Jacqueline Beecroft\n| home_town      = [[London]] and [[Oxford]], England\n| children       =\n}}\n\n'''Paul Adrian Barlow Beecroft''' (born [[Yorkshire]], 20 May 1947<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=JiyMi1qc8tMfb1IhqEwzeQ&scan=1|title=Index entry |accessdate=25 May 2012 |work=FreeBMD|publisher=ONS}}</ref>) is a [[British People|British]] [[venture capitalist]] based in [[London]]. He was for many years [[Chief Investment Officer]] of the [[private equity]] group [[Apax]]. He was until recently [[Chairman]] of Dawn Capital.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dawncapital.co.uk/ |title=Home |publisher=Dawn Capital |date= |accessdate=2012-05-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Apax veteran Beecroft returns to VC roots|work=Financial News|date=25 May 2010|url=http://www.efinancialnews.com/story/2010-05-25/adrian-beecroft-dawn-capital}}</ref>\n\nAmong the companies in which Beecroft has personally invested are [[Mimecast]] and Insignis.{{fact|date=April 2020}}\n\nBeecroft has donated more than \u00a3500,000 to the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] since 2006.<ref>{{cite news|title=Beecroft proposals: how Tory donor's radical blueprint split the government|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=23 May 2012|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2012/may/23/beecroft-proposals-coalition-support-criticism|location=UK}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nAdrian Beecroft was born and raised in [[Yorkshire]]. He studied at [[Hymers College]] in [[Kingston upon Hull|Hull]].<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/3664641/The-New-Philanthropists.html|title=The New Philanthropists|last=Thomas|first=David|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=2007-04-20|access-date=2018-09-04|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\nHe graduated from [[Queen's College, Oxford]] with a first class honours degree in [[Physics]] in 1968 and is now an Honorary Fellow of the College.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=85311&privcapId=35903973|title=Profile: Adrian Beecroft|website=www.bloomberg.com|access-date=2018-09-04}}</ref>  In 1976 he gained a M.B.A from Harvard Business School, where he studied as a [[Harkness Fellowship|Harkness Fellow]].<ref name=\":0\" />  He graduated from Harvard as a [[Baker scholar|Baker Scholar]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Career==\nAdrian Beecroft has an extensive career in venture capital and private equity, specialising in IT investments.<ref name=\":0\" />  He was the Chairman of the [[British Venture Capital Association]] in 1991.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/business-big-shot-adrian-beecroft-032nzk2kkxq|title=Business big shot: Adrian Beecroft|date=2010-05-25|work=The Times|access-date=2018-09-04|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref>\n\nBeecroft started his career at [[International Computers Limited|ICL]], in the computer industry.<ref name=\":1\" />  In 1973, he moved to Ocean Transport and Trading Ltd., working to develop their new business area of bulk shipping.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nAfter graduating from [[Harvard Business School]], he joined [[Boston Consulting Group]] in [[London]]. He became Vice President of BCG in 1982.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn 1984, Beecroft joined Apax Partners, and was there for 25 years until he retired from his role as [[Chief investment officer|Chief Investment Officer]] in 2008.<ref name=\":1\" /> While working at Apax, he served as their representative on the boards of over 20 public and private companies, including [[Computacenter]], Alkane Energy and [[Healthcare at Home]]. He played a significant part in the international expansion of the business, which now has over $20 billion under management.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.crunchbase.com/person/adrian-beecroft|title=Adrian Beecroft|website=Crunchbase|language=en|access-date=2018-09-04}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2006, Beecroft was appointed to the [[NESTA]] Investment Committee.<ref>http://www.official-documents.gov.uk/document/hc0607/hc06/0654/0654.pdf</ref> At that time NESTA was still a [[QUANGO]].\n\nBeecroft was awarded the BVCA's Hall of Fame honour at the Private Equity Awards in 2009.<ref name=\":0\" />  He was a member of [[Sir David Walker|Sir David Walker's]] committee on improving the transparency of the private equity industry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ftalphaville.ft.com/2007/03/21/3305/walker-assembles-high-flying-private-equity-working-group/|title=Walker Assembles High Flying Private Equity Working Group|website=ftalphaville.ft.com|language=en|access-date=2018-09-04}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Beecroft joined Dawn Capital as the Chairman of their board.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Beecroft Report and controversy==\nOn 21 May 2012, the [[Beecroft Report]] caused considerable controversy in the UK due to its recommendations to relax regulation surrounding the dismissal of employees. The report claimed this would help to boost the economy.<ref>{{cite news|title=How Adrian Beecroft proposed to rip up decades of employee rights to boost the economy|author=Daily Telegraph|date=21 May 2012|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/9275558/Analysis-How-Adrian-Beecroft-proposed-to-rip-up-decades-of-employee-rights-to-boost-the-economy.html|location=London|work=The Daily Telegraph}}</ref> It was alleged that significant sections of the report had been doctored.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite news|title=Controversial Beecroft report on employment reform doctored by No 10|author=Daily Telegraph|date=21 May 2012|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/9281161/Controversial-Beecroft-report-on-employment-reform-doctored-by-No-10.html|location=London|work=The Daily Telegraph}}</ref> It was also reported that some recommendations had been removed from the original draft of the report.<ref name=\":2\" /> On 21 May [[Secretary of State for Business]] [[Vince Cable]] condemned the report, saying it was unnecessary for the government to scare workers.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-18155827 |title=BBC News - Adrian Beecroft work report not doctored, No 10 says |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date= 2012-05-22|accessdate=2012-05-22}}</ref> Beecroft responded by accusing Cable of being a socialist.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/9283748/Socialist-Vince-Cable-not-fit-for-office-says-Adrian-Beecroft.html|title='Socialist' Vince Cable not fit for office, says Adrian Beecroft|last=Winnett|first=Robert|date=2012-05-22|access-date=2018-09-05|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> He referenced his own experience of having to pay \u00a3150,000 for unfairly dismissing an HR employee as one of the many reasons behind the recommendation in the report.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/9283748/Socialist-Vince-Cable-not-fit-for-office-says-Adrian-Beecroft.html |title='Socialist' Vince Cable not fit for office, says Adrian Beecroft |publisher=Telegraph |date=2011-05-31 |accessdate=2012-05-22 |location=London |first=Robert |last=Winnett}}</ref>\n\n==Philanthropy==\n[[File:Beecroft Bldg Oxford.jpg|thumb|The Beecroft Building viewed from [[Parks Road]], [[Oxford]], completed in 2018]]\n\nBeecroft helped to found and funds the Beecroft Institute of Particle Physics and Cosmology (BIPAC)<ref name=\":3\" /> at [[Oxford University]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.physics.ox.ac.uk/astro/bipac/ |title=Beecroft Institute of Particle Astrophysics and Cosmology |publisher=Physics.ox.ac.uk |date= |accessdate=2012-05-22}}</ref> He has also part-funded the [[Beecroft Building]], part of the [[Department of Physics, University of Oxford|Department of Physics]] in Oxford. This new building is specifically focused on [[Theoretical physics|theoretical]], [[Condensed matter physics|condensed matter]] and [[Quantum (physics)|quantum]] physics. According to ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', the funding for this building was inspired by Beecroft's interest in [[astrophysics]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.campaign.ox.ac.uk/news/beecroft-building|title=Celebrating the \u2018bottoming out\u2019 of Oxford\u2019s Beecroft Building|website=www.campaign.ox.ac.uk|language=en-gb|access-date=2018-09-07}}</ref><ref name=\":3\" />\n\nBeecroft has supported his school, Hymer's College in Hull.<ref name=\":3\" />  He has also been a Trustee of Impetus Trust, a social impact charity.<ref name=\":3\" /> Beecroft was also for six years the Chairman of the Cricket Foundation, now known as [[Chance to Shine]], a charity focused on bringing cricket back into British state school education.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chancetoshine.org/news/cricket-foundation-elects-donald-brydon-as-new-chairman-of-the-board-of-trustees|title=Cricket Foundation elects Donald Brydon as new Chairman of the Board of Trustees|website=www.chancetoshine.org|language=en|access-date=2018-09-07}}</ref>\n\nThrough the Beecroft Trust, Adrian and his wife sponsor the [[Oxford Academy, Oxfordshire|Oxford Academy]], an Academy school serving a very deprived area of Oxford.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theoxfordacademy.org.uk/Sponsors|title=Sponsors|website=www.theoxfordacademy.org.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-09-07}}</ref> Since becoming an Academy school in 2010, its results have improved dramatically from 14% of the students achieving five A* to C grades including English and Maths to 56% achieving this in 2017. However, in 2019 only 17% of pupils achieved grade 5 or above at GCSE and the school had the worst Attainment 8 and Progress 8 scores of any mainstream school in Oxfordshire.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oxfordmail.co.uk/news/17988398.gcse-2019-results-oxford-academy-disappointed/|title=School 'disappointed' to come bottom in GCSE rankings|website=Oxford Mail|language=en|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref> In December 2019 the Head and governing body were removed after an [[Ofsted|OFSTED]] inspection.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oxfordmail.co.uk/news/18090495.head-governors-leave-oxford-academy-ofsted/|title=Mum says school is 'like juvey' as head and governors leave|website=Oxford Mail|language=en|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref>\n\nMr Beecroft has also supported the [[UNESCO]] initiative to preserve the [[Belize Barrier Reef]] Reserve System, which was classified as in danger on the UNESCO List of World Heritage in Danger in 2009.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/news/1839/|title=Landmark Conservation Action leads to Belize Barrier Reef removal from List of World Heritage in Danger|last=Centre|first=UNESCO World Heritage|website=whc.unesco.org|language=en|access-date=2018-09-07}}</ref>  As of June 2018, the [[World Heritage Committee]] decided to remove the Belize Barrier Reef, which is the world's second largest coral reef, from the list.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-44627719|title=Belize reef taken off 'in danger' list|date=2018-06-27|work=BBC News|access-date=2018-09-07|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Aston Martin DBR1 Adrian Beecroft.jpg|thumb|Adrian Beecroft in his [[Aston Martin DBR1]]]]\nBeecroft lives in [[London]] and supports [[Lord's|Lord's Cricket Ground]] as a [[Marylebone Cricket Club]] (MCC) Trustee.<ref name=\":4\">{{Citation|last=Lord's Cricket Ground|title=Meet MCC Trustee Adrian Beecroft {{!}} MCC/Lord's|date=2015-09-29|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QqN_NLDNxVw|access-date=2018-09-07}}</ref>  As a trustee one of his core roles is assisting with the appointment of the Chairman, but also overseeing the wellbeing of the club and cricket ground.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lords.org/mcc/the-club/mcc-committee/|title=MCC Committee|website=www.lords.org|language=en|access-date=2018-09-07}}</ref> His enthusiasm for the sport came from watching the [[Yorkshire County Cricket Club|Yorkshire County team]] play in Hull.<ref name=\":4\" />  He is the President of Cropredy Cricket Club for whom he still plays league cricket.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://cropredycc.play-cricket.com/website/player_stats_widget/batting_stats/142168|title=Cropredy CC|website=cropredycc.play-cricket.com|language=en|access-date=2018-09-07}}</ref>\n\nBeecroft is a supporter of the [[North Yorkshire Moors Railway]] of which he is a Vice-President. He is a keen auto-enthusiast, having an extensive collection of vehicles, including several [[Aston Martin]]s, most notably a [[Aston Martin DBR1|DBR1]] which he races at a number of motoring events and later crashed in 2015.<ref>http://carbuzz.com/m/Article.aspx?Id=29621</ref> He is a governor of [[Hymers College]] in Hull.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{commoncat inline|Adrian Beecroft}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Beecroft, Adrian}}\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:People educated at Hymers College]]\n[[Category:Alumni of The Queen's College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Harvard Business School alumni]]\n[[Category:Harkness Fellows]]\n[[Category:Angel investors]]\n[[Category:British businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name           = Adrian Beecroft\n| image          =\n| image_size     =\n| caption        =\n| birth_date     = 20 May 1947\n| birth_place    = [[Yorkshire]], [[England]]\n| death_place    =\n| education      = [[Hymers College]]<br/>[[Queen's College, Oxford]]<br/>[[Harvard Business School]]\n| occupation     = [[Angel investor]]\n| spouse         = Jacqueline Beecroft\n| home_town      = [[London]] and [[Oxford]], England\n| children       =\n}}\n\n'''Paul Adrian Barlow Beecroft''' (born [[Yorkshire]], 20 May 1947<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=JiyMi1qc8tMfb1IhqEwzeQ&scan=1|title=Index entry |accessdate=25 May 2012 |work=FreeBMD|publisher=ONS}}</ref>) is a [[British People|British]] [[venture capitalist]] based in [[London]]. He was for many years [[Chief Investment Officer]] of the [[private equity]] group [[Apax]]. He was until recently [[Chairman]] of Dawn Capital.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dawncapital.co.uk/ |title=Home |publisher=Dawn Capital |date= |accessdate=2012-05-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Apax veteran Beecroft returns to VC roots|work=Financial News|date=25 May 2010|url=http://www.efinancialnews.com/story/2010-05-25/adrian-beecroft-dawn-capital}}</ref>\n\nAmong the companies in which Beecroft has personally invested are [[Mimecast]] and Insignis.{{fact|date=April 2020}}\n\nBeecroft has donated more than \u00a3500,000 to the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] since 2006.<ref>{{cite news|title=Beecroft proposals: how Tory donor's radical blueprint split the government|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=23 May 2012|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2012/may/23/beecroft-proposals-coalition-support-criticism|location=UK}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nAdrian Beecroft was born and raised in [[Yorkshire]]. He studied at [[Hymers College]] in [[Hull]].<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/3664641/The-New-Philanthropists.html|title=The New Philanthropists|last=Thomas|first=David|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=2007-04-20|access-date=2018-09-04|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\nHe graduated from [[Queen's College, Oxford]] with a first class honours degree in [[Physics]] in 1968 and is now an Honorary Fellow of the College.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=85311&privcapId=35903973|title=Profile: Adrian Beecroft|website=www.bloomberg.com|access-date=2018-09-04}}</ref>  In 1976 he gained a M.B.A from Harvard Business School, where he studied as a [[Harkness Fellowship|Harkness Fellow]].<ref name=\":0\" />  He graduated from Harvard as a [[Baker scholar|Baker Scholar]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Career==\nAdrian Beecroft has an extensive career in venture capital and private equity, specialising in IT investments.<ref name=\":0\" />  He was the Chairman of the [[British Venture Capital Association]] in 1991.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/business-big-shot-adrian-beecroft-032nzk2kkxq|title=Business big shot: Adrian Beecroft|date=2010-05-25|work=The Times|access-date=2018-09-04|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref>\n\nBeecroft started his career at [[International Computers Limited|ICL]], in the computer industry.<ref name=\":1\" />  In 1973, he moved to Ocean Transport and Trading Ltd., working to develop their new business area of bulk shipping.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nAfter graduating from [[Harvard Business School]], he joined [[Boston Consulting Group]] in [[London]]. He became Vice President of BCG in 1982.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn 1984, Beecroft joined Apax Partners, and was there for 25 years until he retired from his role as [[Chief investment officer|Chief Investment Officer]] in 2008.<ref name=\":1\" /> While working at Apax, he served as their representative on the boards of over 20 public and private companies, including [[Computacenter]], Alkane Energy and [[Healthcare at Home]]. He played a significant part in the international expansion of the business, which now has over $20 billion under management.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.crunchbase.com/person/adrian-beecroft|title=Adrian Beecroft|website=Crunchbase|language=en|access-date=2018-09-04}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2006, Beecroft was appointed to the [[NESTA]] Investment Committee.<ref>http://www.official-documents.gov.uk/document/hc0607/hc06/0654/0654.pdf</ref> At that time NESTA was still a [[QUANGO]].\n\nBeecroft was awarded the BVCA's Hall of Fame honour at the Private Equity Awards in 2009.<ref name=\":0\" />  He was a member of [[Sir David Walker|Sir David Walker's]] committee on improving the transparency of the private equity industry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ftalphaville.ft.com/2007/03/21/3305/walker-assembles-high-flying-private-equity-working-group/|title=Walker Assembles High Flying Private Equity Working Group|website=ftalphaville.ft.com|language=en|access-date=2018-09-04}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Beecroft joined Dawn Capital as the Chairman of their board.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Beecroft Report and controversy==\nOn 21 May 2012, the [[Beecroft Report]] caused considerable controversy in the UK due to its recommendations to relax regulation surrounding the dismissal of employees. The report claimed this would help to boost the economy.<ref>{{cite news|title=How Adrian Beecroft proposed to rip up decades of employee rights to boost the economy|author=Daily Telegraph|date=21 May 2012|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/9275558/Analysis-How-Adrian-Beecroft-proposed-to-rip-up-decades-of-employee-rights-to-boost-the-economy.html|location=London|work=The Daily Telegraph}}</ref> It was alleged that significant sections of the report had been doctored.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite news|title=Controversial Beecroft report on employment reform doctored by No 10|author=Daily Telegraph|date=21 May 2012|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/9281161/Controversial-Beecroft-report-on-employment-reform-doctored-by-No-10.html|location=London|work=The Daily Telegraph}}</ref> It was also reported that some recommendations had been removed from the original draft of the report.<ref name=\":2\" /> On 21 May [[Secretary of State for Business]] [[Vince Cable]] condemned the report, saying it was unnecessary for the government to scare workers.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-18155827 |title=BBC News - Adrian Beecroft work report not doctored, No 10 says |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date= 2012-05-22|accessdate=2012-05-22}}</ref> Beecroft responded by accusing Cable of being a socialist.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/9283748/Socialist-Vince-Cable-not-fit-for-office-says-Adrian-Beecroft.html|title='Socialist' Vince Cable not fit for office, says Adrian Beecroft|last=Winnett|first=Robert|date=2012-05-22|access-date=2018-09-05|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> He referenced his own experience of having to pay \u00a3150,000 for unfairly dismissing an HR employee as one of the many reasons behind the recommendation in the report.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/9283748/Socialist-Vince-Cable-not-fit-for-office-says-Adrian-Beecroft.html |title='Socialist' Vince Cable not fit for office, says Adrian Beecroft |publisher=Telegraph |date=2011-05-31 |accessdate=2012-05-22 |location=London |first=Robert |last=Winnett}}</ref>\n\n==Philanthropy==\n[[File:Beecroft Bldg Oxford.jpg|thumb|The Beecroft Building viewed from [[Parks Road]], [[Oxford]], completed in 2018]]\n\nBeecroft helped to found and funds the Beecroft Institute of Particle Physics and Cosmology (BIPAC)<ref name=\":3\" /> at [[Oxford University]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.physics.ox.ac.uk/astro/bipac/ |title=Beecroft Institute of Particle Astrophysics and Cosmology |publisher=Physics.ox.ac.uk |date= |accessdate=2012-05-22}}</ref> He has also part-funded the [[Beecroft Building]], part of the [[Department of Physics, University of Oxford|Department of Physics]] in Oxford. This new building is specifically focused on [[Theoretical physics|theoretical]], [[Condensed matter physics|condensed matter]] and [[Quantum (physics)|quantum]] physics. According to ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', the funding for this building was inspired by Beecroft's interest in [[astrophysics]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.campaign.ox.ac.uk/news/beecroft-building|title=Celebrating the \u2018bottoming out\u2019 of Oxford\u2019s Beecroft Building|website=www.campaign.ox.ac.uk|language=en-gb|access-date=2018-09-07}}</ref><ref name=\":3\" />\n\nBeecroft has supported his school, Hymer's College in Hull.<ref name=\":3\" />  He has also been a Trustee of Impetus Trust, a social impact charity.<ref name=\":3\" /> Beecroft was also for six years the Chairman of the Cricket Foundation, now known as [[Chance to Shine]], a charity focused on bringing cricket back into British state school education.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chancetoshine.org/news/cricket-foundation-elects-donald-brydon-as-new-chairman-of-the-board-of-trustees|title=Cricket Foundation elects Donald Brydon as new Chairman of the Board of Trustees|website=www.chancetoshine.org|language=en|access-date=2018-09-07}}</ref>\n\nThrough the Beecroft Trust, Adrian and his wife sponsor the [[Oxford Academy, Oxfordshire|Oxford Academy]], an Academy school serving a very deprived area of Oxford.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theoxfordacademy.org.uk/Sponsors|title=Sponsors|website=www.theoxfordacademy.org.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-09-07}}</ref> Since becoming an Academy school in 2010, its results have improved dramatically from 14% of the students achieving five A* to C grades including English and Maths to 56% achieving this in 2017. However, in 2019 only 17% of pupils achieved grade 5 or above at GCSE and the school had the worst Attainment 8 and Progress 8 scores of any mainstream school in Oxfordshire.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oxfordmail.co.uk/news/17988398.gcse-2019-results-oxford-academy-disappointed/|title=School 'disappointed' to come bottom in GCSE rankings|website=Oxford Mail|language=en|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref> In December 2019 the Head and governing body were removed after an [[Ofsted|OFSTED]] inspection.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oxfordmail.co.uk/news/18090495.head-governors-leave-oxford-academy-ofsted/|title=Mum says school is 'like juvey' as head and governors leave|website=Oxford Mail|language=en|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref>\n\nMr Beecroft has also supported the [[UNESCO]] initiative to preserve the [[Belize Barrier Reef]] Reserve System, which was classified as in danger on the UNESCO List of World Heritage in Danger in 2009.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/news/1839/|title=Landmark Conservation Action leads to Belize Barrier Reef removal from List of World Heritage in Danger|last=Centre|first=UNESCO World Heritage|website=whc.unesco.org|language=en|access-date=2018-09-07}}</ref>  As of June 2018, the [[World Heritage Committee]] decided to remove the Belize Barrier Reef, which is the world's second largest coral reef, from the list.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-44627719|title=Belize reef taken off 'in danger' list|date=2018-06-27|work=BBC News|access-date=2018-09-07|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Aston Martin DBR1 Adrian Beecroft.jpg|thumb|Adrian Beecroft in his [[Aston Martin DBR1]]]]\nBeecroft lives in [[London]] and supports [[Lord's|Lord's Cricket Ground]] as a [[Marylebone Cricket Club]] (MCC) Trustee.<ref name=\":4\">{{Citation|last=Lord's Cricket Ground|title=Meet MCC Trustee Adrian Beecroft {{!}} MCC/Lord's|date=2015-09-29|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QqN_NLDNxVw|access-date=2018-09-07}}</ref>  As a trustee one of his core roles is assisting with the appointment of the Chairman, but also overseeing the wellbeing of the club and cricket ground.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lords.org/mcc/the-club/mcc-committee/|title=MCC Committee|website=www.lords.org|language=en|access-date=2018-09-07}}</ref> His enthusiasm for the sport came from watching the [[Yorkshire County Cricket Club|Yorkshire County team]] play in Hull.<ref name=\":4\" />  He is the President of Cropredy Cricket Club for whom he still plays league cricket.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://cropredycc.play-cricket.com/website/player_stats_widget/batting_stats/142168|title=Cropredy CC|website=cropredycc.play-cricket.com|language=en|access-date=2018-09-07}}</ref>\n\nBeecroft is a supporter of the [[North Yorkshire Moors Railway]] of which he is a Vice-President. He is a keen auto-enthusiast, having an extensive collection of vehicles, including several [[Aston Martin]]s, most notably a [[Aston Martin DBR1|DBR1]] which he races at a number of motoring events and later crashed in 2015.<ref>http://carbuzz.com/m/Article.aspx?Id=29621</ref> He is a governor of [[Hymers College]] in Hull.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{commoncat inline|Adrian Beecroft}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Beecroft, Adrian}}\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:People educated at Hymers College]]\n[[Category:Alumni of The Queen's College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Harvard Business School alumni]]\n[[Category:Harkness Fellows]]\n[[Category:Angel investors]]\n[[Category:British businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) people]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:Hull\u2192Kingston upon Hull", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adrian_Beecroft"}
